comments.content: FRAT1 interacts with DVL1 and stabilizes beta-catenin in COS-7 cells.
On WNT3A stimulation, DVL3 interacts with AXIN1 in NIH-3T3 cells.
On Wnt3A stimulation CTNNB1 interacts with CCND1 in Human HEK293, Mouse L929, Mouse MEF cells respectively.
On Wnt3A stimulation CTNNB1 interacts with CDK6 in Human HEK293, Mouse L929, Mouse MEF cells respectively.
WNT5A stimulates autophosphorylation of NLK in PC12 cells.
On WNT stimualtion, PKC alpha phosphorylates DVL-2 in HEK293 cells.
On WNT stimualtion, PKC beta phosphorylates DVL-2 in HEK293 cells.
On WNT stimualtion, PKC gamma phosphorylates DVL-2 in HEK293 cells.
On WNT stimulation, DVL2 interacts with TSC1 in HEK293T cells.
WNT1 induces interaction of TCF3 with Beta catenin in Mouse C57MG cells.
WNT5A and WNT1 stimulates autophosphorylation of TAK1 in HEK293T cells.
Wnt1 induces the phosphorylation of DVL3 by PAR-1 beta in CHO cells

Dvl can stimulate the formation of PIP2 by sequential actions of PI4K2A and PIP5K1B. Both PDZ and DEP domains could interact with PI4K2A, whereas the DIX domain binds to and activates PIP5K1B. The three proteins form a ternary complex upon WNT3A stimulation. The resultant PIP2 is required for WNT3A-induced clustering and phosphorylation of LRP6 in HEK 293T cells.
GSK3B, AXIN and APC form a destruction complex that induces beta-catenin degradation in 293T cells.
On WNT1 stimulation, MAP3K7 translocates from cytoplasm to nucleus in CV-1 cells.

On stimulation with WNT3A, CTNNB1 translocates from cytosol to nucleus in Mouse C3H10T1/2, Human HEK293,Human mesenchymal stem cells, Human preosteoblasts and Human primary myeloma cells, rat oval cell line WB-F344, rat heart cell line H9C2,Human osteoblasts and Mouse NIH3T3 cells.
TCF4 forms a complex with beta-catenin and BCL9
WNT1 induces interaction of TCF4 with Beta catenin in Mouse C57MG cells.
beta-catenin interacts with LEF1 upon WNT1 stimulation in 293 and C57MG cells
SOX1 interacts with beta-catenin and suppresses beta-catenin mediated TCF/LEF signaling
On WNT stimulation, phosphorylation of TSC1 by GSK3 affects TSC1-TSC2 interaction in HEK 293T cells and in vitro.
On WNT1 stimulation, DVL1 interacts with RAC in HEK293T cells
Interaction between GSK3B and CTNNB1_APC.
GSK-3 beta forms a complex with AXIN and beta-catenin and can block signaling induced by WNT
On WNT3A stimulation, WNT/beta-catenin pathway induces upregulation of c-Myc expression in HUVECs and Human HEK293 cells.
Wnt stimulates the phosphorylation of LRP6 by GSK3A/B at Ser 1490, Ser 1590, Ser 1607, Thr 1530 and Thr 1572
Wnt inhibits GSK3-mediated phosphorylation of TSC2, a tumor suppressor which negatively regulates mTOR,thereby activating mTOR-mediated translational regulation in tumorigenesis.
On WNT1 stimulation LRP6 interacts with AXIN1 in Human HEK293 cells.

The dynamic polymerization of Dvl correlates with its ability to activate Wnt/Î²-catenin signaling. Dvl is recruited by Fz via its PDZ domain and oligomerizes via its DIX domain at the plasma membrane
On WNT1 and WNT5 stimulation, Wnt/Î²-Catenin/Tcf Signaling pathway induces upregulation of AXIN2 expression in C57MG and MDA MB 231 breast carcinoma cells.
On WNT1, WNT3A and WNT5A  stimualtion, downstream effects via b-catenin/TCF and b-catenin/LEF dependent regulation of transcription leads to upregulation of GJA1 expression in HUVECs, PC12 cells .

comments.content: WNT signal, through the canonical pathway, controls cell fate determination and through the non-canonical pathway controls cell movement and tissue polarity. The name "wnt" is a fusion of two terms, wg derived from the Drosophila gene wingless (wg) and int derived from the proto-oncogene integration-1, which is the mammalian homolog of wg. ÃŸ-catenin is the key regulated effector of Wnt, involved in canonical signaling . Free ÃŸ-catenin is bound by a multiprotein "destruction complex". The ÃŸ-catenin destruction complex is comprised of ÃŸ-catenin, scaffold proteins (APC, AXIN) and serine/threonine kinases that phosphorylate ÃŸ-catenin casein kinase 1 (CSNK1A1, CSNK1D, CSNK1E, CSNK1G1) and GSK3B. The sequential phosphorylation of ÃŸ-catenin by casein kinase 1 and GSK3 is recognised by an SCF-class E3-ubiquitin ligase, which targets it for polyubiquitination and proteosomal destruction. Canonical WNT signals are transduced through a two-part receptor, a seven-transmembrane Frizzled (FZD) and low density lipoprotein receptor-related protein 5/6 (LRP5/LRP6) to a ÃŸ-catenin (CTNNB1) signaling cascade. On recruitment of deshevelled (DVL1) to FZD and AXIN to LRP6, ÃŸ-catenin destruction complex disassembles leading to its stabilization and nuclear accumulation. Nuclear ÃŸ-catenin binds to T-cell factor/lymphoid enhancer factor (TCF/LEF) family of transcription factors and Legless family docking protein, BCL9. These activate the transcription of Wnt target genes CCND1, MYC. Non-canonical WNT signaling diverges downstream after being transduced through FZD family receptors and co-receptors, ROR2 and RYK. This pathway does not involve ÃŸ-catenin-mediated gene expression. Small G proteins such as RAC1, RHOA and downstream effectors of RAC including JNK are DVL-dependant effector molecules of the non-canonical pathway. These have been implicated in cytoskeletal rearrangement, dendrite growth and control of cell polarity and orientation. Nemo-like kinase (NLK) and nuclear factor of activated T cells (NFAT) are Ca2+-dependant effectors of the non-canonical pathway. NLK inhibits canonical pathway by phosphorylation of TCF/LEF family transcription factors. NFAT transcription factor is implicated in convergent extension during early embryogenesis and carcinogenic metastasis.
